Scikit-Learn Cluster Analysis

  • Mon 28 November 2016
  • ·
  • scikit-learn
  • ·
  • python, scikit-learn, cluster analysis, K-Means, Gaussian Mixture Models

The following will apply cluster analysis techniques to understand the Enron emails dataset sourced from here. This supplies information on Enron emails in a bag-of-words format, giving the count for each word.

This will be done in the following ways:

  • K-Means
  • Gaussian Mixture Models

Word Clouds will also be explored as a tool for understanding the theme of a given cluster.

Metadata

The provided metadata states that the documents are structured as thus:

vocab.enron.txt docword.enron.txt
word 1 # Documents
word 2 # Words in vocabulary
word 3 # Nonzero counts
word 4 docID wordID count
... ...

Loading and Organising the data

First we import pandas - see here for a guide on how to use:

Feature Engineering

The above provides a bag of words model for each document - the order of the words are ignored, and the number of instances of each word is counted, giving a word count vector to represent each document.

TF-IDF

We assume that the most important words for email comparison are those which are rare across all emails but common in a specific email. Under a bag of words model, words that are common across all emails (and so are of little value in comparison) dominate. To account for this, we use a Term Frequency Inverse Document Frequency (TF-IDF) representation of documents.

We import NumPy for its functionality:

In [10]:
import numpy as np

To test drive our approach, first a test dataset is created:

In [11]:
test_data = pd.DataFrame({
    'a': [10,20,0,0],
    'b': [20,10,11,10],
    'c': [30,0,0,0,],
})

test_data
Out[11]:
a b c
0 10 20 30
1 20 10 0
2 0 11 0
3 0 10 0

The TF-IDF values for word a in documents 1 and 2 should be:

In [12]:
test_no_docs = 4
test_no_docs_using_a = 2

IDF_a = np.log(float(test_no_docs) / (1 + test_no_docs_using_a))

TF_doc_0_word_a = 10
TF_doc_1_word_a = 20

print("TF-IDF for word a in doc 0: " + str(TF_doc_0_word_a * IDF_a))

print("TF-IDF for word a in doc 1: " + str(TF_doc_1_word_a * IDF_a))

TF-IDF for word a in doc 0: 2.87682072452
TF-IDF for word a in doc 1: 5.75364144904

Implementing TF-IDF function to apply across data frame, using the above to test the result:

In [13]:
def TF_IDF(test_data):
    #Total number of docs:
    test_no_docs = len(test_data)
    IDF_dict = {name: np.log(float(test_no_docs) / (1 + len(test_data[test_data[name] > 0]))) for name in test_data.columns}
    new_data = pd.DataFrame()
    for name in test_data.columns:
        new_data[name] = test_data[name] * IDF_dict[name]
    return(new_data)

test_data = TF_IDF(test_data)

Data Analysis

The above has created a table (TF_IDF_data), where each row corresponds to an email, and consists of a list of TF-IDF values for each word.

We will now apply K-Means and Gaussian Mixture Models using scikit-learn:

In [17]:
from sklearn import cluster

K-Means

K-Means is chosen with the following parameters:

  • 8 clusters (n_clusters);
  • initial cluster centres chosen using K-Means++ (init);
  • the algorithm will be run 10 times using different centroid seeds, with the best chosen using inertia (n_init);
  • convergence is declared when inertia falls below 1e-4 (tol);
  • we have overriden the default number of CPUs used (n_jobs) from no parallel computing (1) - eases debugging - to all CPUS (-1); and
  • seed for the random selection of initial centres set to 1 (random_state)
In [18]:
kmeans = cluster.KMeans(n_clusters = 8
                       , init = 'k-means++'
                       , n_init = 10
                       , tol = 0.0001
                       , n_jobs = -1
                       , random_state = 1)
In [19]:
kmeans.fit(norm_data)

We could also represent the above clusters using word clouds - to get a broader perspective on the data. We use Andreas Mueller's Python package, with details given here:

In [36]:
from wordcloud import WordCloud
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline
In [38]:
for i in range(0, len(centroids)):
    wordcloud = WordCloud(background_color = 'white')
    kMeansWordCloud = wordcloud.generate_from_frequencies(tuple(tuple(centroids.T[i].reset_index().values)))
    plt.figure()
    plt.imshow(kMeansWordCloud)
    plt.axis("off")

The above used a very simple K-Means analysis, using an arbitrary number of clusters. Despite this, there does seem to be clear themes in the Enron emails - the following groups of emails seem to be present:

  1. Projects - particularly discussing rent, cost and loans
  2. Setting up meetings - particularly concerning availability ('free')
  3. Regarding instructions that have been made - which seem to be mainly with 'Paine Webber'
  4. Coin-flipping game
  5. Resource requests
  6. Strategic meetings mainly with BMC (and some other Houston-based companies, e.g., compaq)
  7. Gas Market
  8. Investment recommendations with communications mainly with Merrill Lynch

Note that UBS PaineWebber provided Enron employees with stock option services.

Gaussian Mixture Models

Gaussian Mixture Models enable a wider range of elliptically shaped clusters to be considered, with the weights on different features being learnt, rather than having to be pre-specified. They also lead to soft assignment - i.e., different points are assigned probabilities of being in each cluster. However, this comes at a higher computational cost than with K-Means, and Gaussian Mixture Models assume that all of the data points follow multivariate Gaussian distributions.

The sklearn.mixture package is used:

In [24]:
from sklearn import mixture

To enable comparison with K-Means, 8 components are specified. Be careful, the following takes at least 30 minutes to run:

In [25]:
GMM = mixture.GaussianMixture(n_components=8).fit(norm_data)

Extracting the means:

In [26]:
means = pd.DataFrame(GMM.means_)

Understanding GMM.covariances_:

In [27]:
np.shape(GMM.covariances_)
Out[27]:
(8L, 10723L, 10723L)

To extract the variances, we take the diagonal of the covariance matrices - e.g.:

In [28]:
np.diagonal(GMM.covariances_[0])
Out[28]:
array([  1.00000000e-06,   1.00000000e-06,   1.00000000e-06, ...,
         1.00000000e-06,   1.00000000e-06,   1.00000000e-06])

Converting the mean column names into words:

In [29]:
means.columns = TF_IDF_data.columns

Finding the words with the highest mean TF-IDF for each cluster, and the associated variances:

In [44]:
for i in range(0, len(means)):
    display = pd.DataFrame()
    display['means'] = means.ix[i,:]
    display['variances'] = np.diagonal(GMM.covariances_[i])
    print(display.sort_values(by='means', ascending = False)[0:10])
    print("\n")

The above Gaussian Mixture Model suggests the following themes of emails:

  1. Analysing futures (note that Carr Futures used to deal in futures)
  2. Gas Market - similar to K-Means
  3. Buying Instructions
  4. Deleting messages
  5. Resource Requests - similar to K-Means
  6. Zdnet emails
  7. Projects - similar to K-Means
  8. Arranging strategic meetings with BMC and compaq

The 'deleting messages' category is very interesting - the word cloud suggests that a lot of 'prohibited' activity was occurring. Note that ZDNet provides 'news, analysis, comments and product reviews' on technology'.

Comparison of methods

This comparison has showed how the Gaussian Mixture Model can be a lot slower than K-Means. However, it also seemed to provide more informative themes, in particular revealing that message deletion as a possible theme - this could have indicated an issue with illegal activity.

This comparison has also demonstrated how word clouds provide a simple but effective tool for understanding the themes of different clusters - giving a stronger indication of the relative importance of different words, and revealing important words that were not in the top 10.
